@article{MoralesNapoles2012,
abstract = {Bayesian Networks (BNs) are graphical models which allow the representation of a probability distribution over more than one variable. They provide an elegant way of describing how variables depend on each other. Our main goal for this course is that it serves participants as a guide to main concepts and important issues that need to be taken into account when using BNs as modelling tool. Additionally, software applications (some developed within TNO) and their basic operation will be discussed. The audience of the course may include participants with no previous experience with BNs. However some familiarity with modelling in general is required and familiarity with basic probability theory is desirable. In this course we focus on BNs that model the uncertainty about the state of physical systems. However, the concepts to be discussed are general and independent of the field of application. Thus they also hold for applications of BNs in different domains, for example behavioural and cognitive sciences or health related applications to name a couple. The scope of BN applications within TNO is also not restricted to physical systems. As examples of the type of applications carried out within TNO we briefly mention two different types of applications in Appendix A. The first is a set of applications that are aimed at performance measurement of complex systems under various operational circumstances. The second type of BN application is in the area of police investigation and military intelligence. The scope of applications of BNs outside TNO is even broader (for an overview see Weber 2012 et al.). We do not aim to be exhaustive in Appendix A, but merely provide an idea of the type of applications carried out within TNO, outside the examples presented in this document.},
